==German==

===Etymology===
Originally {{prefix|n|immer|lang=de}}, thus the same construct as English {{m|en|ever}} and {{m|en|never}}. Later on there has been interference by unrelated dialectal contractions of {{m|de|nicht mehr}}, as which the word is interpreted by most contemporary speakers.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈnɪmər/|lang=de}}
* {{audio|De-nimmer.ogg|Audio|lang=de}}

===Adverb===
{{head|de|adverb}}

# {{lb|de|regional|chiefly|southern Germany|Austria}} [[no]] [[more]], [[no longer]]
# {{lb|de|regional|chiefly|southern Germany|Austria}} [[never again]]
# {{lb|de|archaic|or|poetic|literary}} [[never]], at no time
#* Espenbaum, Paul Celan:
#*: Meiner Mutter Haar ward '''nimmer''' weiß.

====Usage notes====
* In northern Germany and many parts of central Germany, the word is used mainly in some set phrases such as {{m|de|nie und nimmer||never ever}}. Otherwise it has an archaic or poetic ring to it. It is used more readily in southern Germany and Austria, meaning “no more” or “never again”. The original sense “never, at no time” is now rare.

